WEBVTT

00:13.417 --> 00:16.250
(crowd chatting)

00:16.334 --> 00:18.792
Craig Findley:
Cooper, is everybody inside?

00:18.876 --> 00:21.000
We're gonna have
a new boardroom,

00:21.083 --> 00:23.083
and we should be able
to accommodate more people.

00:23.167 --> 00:26.125
We had no anticipation that
so many would be here today,

00:26.209 --> 00:28.667
so I apologize for the,
for the inconvenience.

00:28.751 --> 00:30.918
Diane Oetting:
Hi, everybody.
(clears throat)

00:31.000 --> 00:32.375
Two years ago,

00:32.459 --> 00:36.751
the board was concerned
by the continued refusal

00:36.834 --> 00:38.584
on the part of Mr. Weger

00:38.667 --> 00:43.292
to accept any responsibility
or express any remorse.

00:43.375 --> 00:46.459
The board felt that
a release at that time

00:46.542 --> 00:49.292
could jeopardize public safety.

00:49.375 --> 00:51.626
This was two years ago.

00:51.709 --> 00:55.000
If you let him go today,

00:55.083 --> 00:58.876
does that mean that
the crime wasn't brutal?

00:58.959 --> 01:02.542
Does that mean
he is expressing remorse?

01:02.626 --> 01:04.375
No.

01:04.459 --> 01:09.083
We've been fighting this
for 40 years.

01:09.167 --> 01:14.751
Our family has been accused
of being part of the mob.

01:14.834 --> 01:19.500
My grandfather was accused
of setting up a hit,

01:19.584 --> 01:22.709
and my grandmother
and her friends

01:22.792 --> 01:28.584
were going out
to look at birds.

01:29.876 --> 01:31.542
Thank you.

01:33.751 --> 01:36.584
-Yes, ma'am.
-I'm Chester's sister.

01:36.667 --> 01:39.375
He is two years older
than what I am.

01:39.459 --> 01:42.083
He was my closest sibling,

01:42.167 --> 01:45.918
and he has always
maintained his innocence.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.125
He has lost his life
as you all know.

01:50.209 --> 01:54.042
I just hope my brother
does not die in prison.

01:54.125 --> 01:56.292
Thank you.

01:56.375 --> 02:00.584
If there's nothing further,
I'll ask Janet to take the roll.

02:00.667 --> 02:03.167
If he receives eight votes,
he will be paroled.

02:03.250 --> 02:05.167
If he does not, he will not.

02:05.250 --> 02:07.959
-Miss Martinez.
-Yes.

02:08.042 --> 02:09.375
-Mr. Fisher.
-Pete Fisher: No.

02:09.459 --> 02:14.167
-Janet Crane: Mr. Ruggiero.
-Joseph Ruggiero: No.

02:14.250 --> 02:17.876
Mary Pruett:
<i>My family has always</i>
<i>been involved in this.</i>

02:17.959 --> 02:21.834
It's not that we put him
on a back-burner and forgot him.

02:21.918 --> 02:23.876
We have lived this.

02:23.959 --> 02:26.375
Not like my brother's
had to live it,

02:26.459 --> 02:29.459
but we have lived this
by trying to help him.

02:29.542 --> 02:31.584
Mr. James.

02:33.209 --> 02:35.375
Oreal James:
Yes.

02:35.459 --> 02:37.959
-Janet: Mr. Brink.
-Daniel Brink: Yes.

02:38.042 --> 02:40.667
-Ms. Crigler.
-Edith Crigler: Yes.

02:40.751 --> 02:43.042
-Ms. Daniels.
-Yes.

02:45.042 --> 02:47.375
-Chairman Findley.
-Findley: Yes.

02:47.459 --> 02:49.292
(Mary sobbing)

02:49.375 --> 02:51.834
(Findley speaking)

03:13.125 --> 03:15.584
You betcha. I will.

03:15.667 --> 03:19.083
(pensive music playing)

03:30.918 --> 03:32.709
♪ ♪

03:44.000 --> 03:45.459
♪ ♪

04:05.167 --> 04:07.167
(car approaching)

04:12.250 --> 04:15.500
(bell tolling)

04:15.584 --> 04:18.375
Kathy Etz:
<i>I don't know if members</i>
<i>of the parole board</i>

04:18.459 --> 04:22.125
<i>felt that, perhaps,
he was innocent,</i>

04:22.209 --> 04:25.167
<i>but it was
extremely traumatizing,</i>

04:25.250 --> 04:28.500
<i>and reopened
the wounds of the tragedy.</i>

04:28.584 --> 04:31.709
<i>The idea that he gets
to be out of prison</i>

04:31.792 --> 04:34.000
<i>while my grandmother is dead,</i>

04:34.083 --> 04:36.709
and I-I'm all for
criminal justice reform,

04:36.792 --> 04:40.250
but that does not mean letting
a murderer out of prison.

04:40.334 --> 04:43.334
So, yeah,
I think that they messed up.

04:44.667 --> 04:47.125
<i>The day that he
was granted parole,</i>

04:47.209 --> 04:49.709
<i>my sister, she just
started sobbing,</i>

04:49.792 --> 04:53.709
and, and said,
"I'm so sorry, Mom," like...

04:53.792 --> 04:56.584
and, um...

04:56.667 --> 04:59.792
you know, I, you know,
my mom was...

04:59.876 --> 05:01.375
you know, just, it was,

05:01.459 --> 05:04.626
it was incredibly
upsetting for all of us.

05:06.584 --> 05:08.417
(sobbing)

05:10.626 --> 05:12.459
Mary:
<i>You couldn't believe</i>
<i>it was happening</i>

05:12.542 --> 05:14.209
<i>after all we have been
through, you know?</i>

05:14.292 --> 05:17.000
You just thought, uh,
"We must be dreaming."

05:17.083 --> 05:19.667
<i>You know, it's been 60 years.</i>

05:19.751 --> 05:21.709
<i>His life is gonna start.</i>

05:21.792 --> 05:23.292
This is your sister.

05:23.375 --> 05:25.584
We just got through
with the parole board,

05:25.667 --> 05:26.751
and it was-- Guess what?

05:26.834 --> 05:28.292
Chester Weger (on phone):
<i>I won.</i>

05:28.375 --> 05:31.083
-(friends cheering)
-Andy Hale:
We're so excited for you.

05:31.167 --> 05:32.417
I can't wait
to see ya in person,

05:32.500 --> 05:34.542
and I know your family
can't wait to see you.

05:34.626 --> 05:37.334
Start living your life,
get out and enjoy freedom.

05:37.417 --> 05:39.459
-We love you.
-Andy: We'll, we'll talk
to you soon.

05:39.542 --> 05:43.125
<i>When I got involved
with Chester's case in 2016,</i>

05:43.209 --> 05:45.792
<i>I had never heard
of the Starved Rock murders.</i>

05:45.876 --> 05:48.542
I wasn't born in 1960,
but I read--

05:48.626 --> 05:51.834
It was a front-page article
in<i> The Chicago Tribune</i>
about Chester Weger,

05:51.918 --> 05:55.083
<i>"Starved Rock Killer
Denied Parole Again," right?</i>

05:55.167 --> 05:57.542
<i>So, I was really intrigued.</i>

05:57.626 --> 06:01.834
<i>This guy's
maintained his innocence
over decades and decades.</i>

06:01.918 --> 06:05.125
So, I decided
to write Chester Weger a letter.

06:07.292 --> 06:09.459
<i>You know, when you look
at false confessions,</i>

06:09.542 --> 06:12.667
<i>and there are certain factors
that lead to wrongful
confessions,</i>

06:12.751 --> 06:14.584
<i>the primary one
is the threat of death.</i>

06:14.667 --> 06:18.375
<i>Here you have uncontested
evidence that Chester</i>

06:18.459 --> 06:21.542
<i>was threatened multiple times
with the death penalty.</i>

06:21.626 --> 06:23.709
<i>The second thing
is all the surveillance.</i>

06:23.792 --> 06:25.500
<i>The thing's
to break somebody's will,</i>

06:25.584 --> 06:28.292
<i>and the coercion
and the techniques,</i>

06:28.375 --> 06:31.167
<i>it has all the hallmarks
of a false confession.</i>

06:31.250 --> 06:35.167
Our first goal was just let's,
let's get him out of prison.

06:35.250 --> 06:37.584
<i>But I think
the more important step</i>

06:37.667 --> 06:40.751
<i>is trying to show people
that he's actually innocent.</i>

06:40.834 --> 06:44.751
Reporter 1:
<i>24 times Chester Weger</i>
<i>was up for parole.</i>

06:44.834 --> 06:47.167
<i>On the 24th try,
parole was granted.</i>

06:47.250 --> 06:48.792
Reporter 2:
<i>The longest-serving prisoner</i>

06:48.876 --> 06:51.459
<i>in Illinois is
about to go free.</i>

06:51.542 --> 06:54.209
DJ (on radio):
<i>Classic Hits 103.9, WLPO</i>

06:54.292 --> 06:56.292
<i>talking about, uh,
Chester Weger's parole.</i>

06:56.375 --> 06:58.500
<i>I wonder if any of this
had to do with the fact</i>

06:58.584 --> 07:01.500
<i>that there's no Tony Raccuglia
to fight to keep him in.</i>

07:01.584 --> 07:03.334
Tom Collins:
<i>I really think</i>
<i>that was part of it,</i>

07:03.417 --> 07:06.209
<i>Tony was such
a vociferous advocate.</i>

07:06.292 --> 07:08.417
DJ:
<i>And credible 'cause</i>
<i>he prosecuted him.</i>

07:08.500 --> 07:10.667
Tom:
<i>Yeah, I really think</i>
<i>that Tony's passing</i>

07:10.751 --> 07:13.125
<i>was not a minor factor
in today's decision.</i>

07:13.209 --> 07:14.542
DJ:
<i>Tom Collins</i>
<i>of</i> The News Tribune,

07:14.626 --> 07:15.834
<i>thank you very much.</i>

07:15.918 --> 07:18.834
Tony Raccuglia died May 2019,

07:18.918 --> 07:21.042
and then,
at the next parole hearing,

07:21.125 --> 07:23.083
Weger is, indeed, paroled,

07:23.167 --> 07:24.667
<i>and can't help but think,</i>

07:24.751 --> 07:27.584
<i>maybe, Tony Raccuglia's
pressure had something
to do with it.</i>

07:27.667 --> 07:32.626
Tony Raccuglia was one
of the most forceful guys I know
when it comes to cases.

07:32.709 --> 07:36.500
<i>Even at his advanced age,
when it came time for
the parole board hearings,</i>

07:36.584 --> 07:38.709
<i>he'd make sure
that those board members</i>

07:38.792 --> 07:42.584
knew how Tony Raccuglia
felt about this case.

07:44.292 --> 07:46.792
Anthony Raccuglia:
<i>You know, Harland Warren</i>
<i>just passed on.</i>

07:46.876 --> 07:50.209
<i>I'm the only living person
that had anything to do</i>

07:50.292 --> 07:52.125
<i>with the prosecution
of that case.</i>

07:52.209 --> 07:55.125
<i>The Sheriff's Office,
they're all dead.</i>

07:55.209 --> 07:58.542
<i>The judge is dead.
The court reporter is dead.</i>

07:58.626 --> 08:00.959
<i>The defense lawyer is dead.</i>

08:01.042 --> 08:02.876
<i>There's just me and Chester.</i>

08:02.959 --> 08:05.334
<i>We're the only two left.</i>

08:05.417 --> 08:08.000
David Raccuglia:
<i>Of course,</i>
<i>I was happy for his family,</i>

08:08.083 --> 08:10.125
<i>that Chester Weger was paroled,</i>

08:10.209 --> 08:12.209
but I was still mourning
the loss of my father,

08:12.292 --> 08:14.250
and they were,
kind of, wrapped up together,

08:14.334 --> 08:17.000
so it was a strange,
emotional time.

08:17.083 --> 08:18.667
<i>The state's attorney
had suggested...</i>

08:18.751 --> 08:21.209
David:
<i>It was my father's death</i>
<i>that made me wanna go back</i>

08:21.292 --> 08:24.584
<i>to a lot of the footage,
and look at it and see him.</i>

08:24.667 --> 08:28.459
<i>It was a, a good
cathartic experience
for me to see him again.</i>

08:28.542 --> 08:30.167
This guy got caught...

08:30.250 --> 08:33.000
David:
<i>But now, there's a potential</i>

08:33.083 --> 08:35.417
<i>wrongful conviction in the air,</i>

08:35.500 --> 08:38.375
<i>and I still--
I had a lot of questions.</i>

08:38.459 --> 08:42.250
I decided it was time for me
to get to the bottom of this.

08:42.334 --> 08:46.083
♪ ♪

08:46.167 --> 08:51.876
<i>And so, I went back to 1960,
and I studied it all.</i>

08:51.959 --> 08:55.417
<i>You know, I, I feel like
I've worked on this case
for so long,</i>

08:55.500 --> 08:59.751
there might not be anything new,
but there was.

09:05.792 --> 09:07.500
(clapping and cheering)

09:07.584 --> 09:08.584
Officer:
If you can get out,
and just go ahead,

09:08.667 --> 09:09.959
and turn the car off, sir.

09:14.876 --> 09:17.209
Chester:
<i>I got a seatbelt.</i>

09:18.459 --> 09:19.959
(Chester speaking)

09:20.042 --> 09:21.584
Person:
He's gonna-- Yeah.

09:24.918 --> 09:26.709
(Man speaking)

09:28.751 --> 09:30.792
Reporter:
<i>Well, is it a good day?</i>

09:32.334 --> 09:34.292
-Reporter: Are you scared?
-No, I'm not.

09:34.375 --> 09:35.751
After all this time,

09:35.834 --> 09:37.459
you've maintained,
your, uh, innocence,

09:37.542 --> 09:40.751
and how does it feel
looking back, 60 years are gone?

09:40.834 --> 09:42.083
(Chester speaking)

09:45.250 --> 09:47.459
Reporter:
How do you feel?
Are you excited?

09:47.542 --> 09:49.125
Yes, I am.

09:50.876 --> 09:53.083
Person 1:
Okay, Dad, start the car up.

09:53.167 --> 09:54.709
-Person 2: Thank you.
-Chester: Thank you.

09:54.792 --> 09:56.834
-Person 2: All right.
-Person 3: Thank you very much.

09:56.918 --> 09:58.250
That don't make sense.

09:58.334 --> 09:59.542
Person:
I know.

10:03.167 --> 10:04.667
DJ:
<i>Old Chester Weger.</i>

10:04.751 --> 10:06.584
<i>After 60 years,</i>

10:06.667 --> 10:09.292
<i>60, 60 trips around the sun,</i>

10:09.375 --> 10:11.876
<i>a man who's never admitted
any wrongdoing,</i>

10:11.959 --> 10:15.667
<i>he's gonna spend
his, uh, remaining years
trying to prove his innocence.</i>

10:24.334 --> 10:25.500
(Johnny Weger speaking)

10:25.584 --> 10:27.167
(Chester speaking)

10:29.751 --> 10:32.000
Get up, old man, get up.

10:32.083 --> 10:33.500
Mwah!

10:33.584 --> 10:35.626
-How are ya?
-I'm all right.

10:35.709 --> 10:38.083
Good, good, looking good.

10:38.167 --> 10:40.876
Ooh, a little skinny.
We need to fatten you up.

10:40.959 --> 10:42.876
Chester:
<i>I'll be all right.</i>

10:42.959 --> 10:44.334
Person:
We just thank you, dear Lord,

10:44.417 --> 10:46.459
that Chester can get out
of imprisonment, Lord,

10:46.542 --> 10:50.417
and just pray that you'll
continue to be with him
and strengthen him, Lord,

10:50.500 --> 10:53.584
and get him back
into, into today's life,
and just watch over him.

10:53.667 --> 10:56.459
In Christ's name
we pray these things, amen.

10:56.542 --> 10:57.876
Amen.

11:02.500 --> 11:07.500
Johnny Weger:
<i>You can't help but think,</i>
<i>"What if?"</i>

11:07.584 --> 11:10.751
What if my dad wasn't in prison?

11:10.834 --> 11:14.792
What if my mom hadn't remarried?
What if, you know?

11:14.876 --> 11:16.167
Oh, Dad.

11:16.250 --> 11:17.667
Son.

11:17.751 --> 11:20.000
You're all right,
come on.

11:20.083 --> 11:22.042
We'll be all right,
we'll be okay.

11:22.125 --> 11:25.209
-I'll be able to see you,
and write to you and everything.
-I know, yeah.

11:25.292 --> 11:27.417
No, I'm just so happy.

11:27.500 --> 11:29.751
I, I know, I'm happy
to see you, too,

11:29.834 --> 11:31.083
and Becky.

11:31.167 --> 11:34.334
Johnny:
<i>He was convicted</i>
<i>of Starved Rock murders,</i>

11:34.417 --> 11:36.709
<i>I was four months old.</i>

11:38.834 --> 11:42.375
<i>I didn't like nobody,
I didn't like myself,</i>

11:42.459 --> 11:45.042
grew hair down to my ass,

11:45.125 --> 11:46.584
put a chip on my shoulder,

11:46.667 --> 11:49.167
and I kept it there
for many years.

11:50.667 --> 11:56.125
<i>For my first burglary,
we did four months together.</i>

11:56.209 --> 11:59.709
That's the most time
I ever spent with my father

11:59.792 --> 12:01.834
was behind bars.

12:04.250 --> 12:06.042
Brian Towne:
<i>This is a horrible crime.</i>

12:06.125 --> 12:07.918
<i>There are families
that have been affected</i>

12:08.000 --> 12:09.959
<i>on both the victims' side
and the defense side.</i>

12:10.042 --> 12:12.250
I mean, Chester Weger's son
has gone to prison,

12:12.334 --> 12:13.751
several times.

12:13.834 --> 12:18.542
<i>A lot of his behavior
has been as a sexual deviant.</i>

12:18.626 --> 12:22.626
<i>It's hard to say if it's
because of him being the son</i>

12:22.709 --> 12:24.167
<i>of the Starved Rock murderer,</i>

12:24.250 --> 12:27.751
<i>or if he's just made
these choices on his own.</i>

12:27.834 --> 12:31.125
Johnny:
<i>All I ever heard</i>
<i>from the courts,</i>

12:31.209 --> 12:36.167
<i>from the people I've met was,
"You're just like your father."</i>

12:36.250 --> 12:38.542
It's gonna affect ya.

12:38.626 --> 12:41.125
<i>61 years old,</i>

12:41.209 --> 12:44.000
<i>the drugs and alcohol
I put in my body,</i>

12:44.083 --> 12:46.500
<i>and the mess
I put my body through.</i>

12:46.584 --> 12:48.792
I'm here.

12:48.876 --> 12:51.167
They say I don't have a brain,

12:51.250 --> 12:52.959
well, let me tell ya this one.

12:53.042 --> 12:55.584
This is called "Woe is Me."

12:55.667 --> 12:58.042
"Again the shadow's loneliness

12:58.125 --> 13:00.834
"have begun to transverse
the passageways of my heart.

13:00.918 --> 13:04.209
"I'm just a lonely prisoner
caged in a man-made hell,

13:04.292 --> 13:07.834
"and this pain and anguish
I suffer is more than
I can tell.

13:07.918 --> 13:10.125
<i>"Memories, without them
I couldn't live,</i>

13:10.209 --> 13:12.626
<i>"for in my mind's eye,
I can see you clearly,</i>

13:12.709 --> 13:15.876
<i>so if there'd be no memories,
then there'd be no you."</i>

13:17.709 --> 13:20.334
<i>I went through 30 years
of prison,</i>

13:20.417 --> 13:23.125
and totally lost my mind.

13:23.209 --> 13:27.125
In prison, that's
all you have is memories.

13:29.000 --> 13:31.792
My father, he taught me

13:31.876 --> 13:37.125
how to love and to care
about somebody besides myself.

13:39.918 --> 13:43.167
<i>They say he's supposed to have
another chance in court,</i>

13:43.250 --> 13:47.626
but they couldn't pay him enough
for 60 years of heartache,

13:47.709 --> 13:50.500
his parents dying,
his wife dying,

13:50.584 --> 13:52.334
his kids suffering.

13:52.417 --> 13:54.584
They couldn't give him enough.

14:07.375 --> 14:08.959
Andy:
<i>I've never been here before.</i>

14:09.042 --> 14:11.751
<i>I can't believe
how scenic it is.</i>

14:11.834 --> 14:13.834
<i>Now that I see this,</i>

14:13.918 --> 14:16.876
<i>you know, the story that
is set forth in the confession</i>

14:16.959 --> 14:18.959
<i>makes zero sense.</i>

14:19.042 --> 14:20.250
<i>And how high it is.</i>

14:20.334 --> 14:22.375
All the struggle to get
the bodies up here,

14:22.459 --> 14:24.292
which, how long's
that gonna take you?

14:24.375 --> 14:27.751
And risk having somebody else
walk into the canyon?

14:27.834 --> 14:31.209
That to me is the bigger risk,
not a plane in the sky.

14:31.292 --> 14:32.876
There's hikers,
there's people here.

14:32.959 --> 14:37.834
To drag three grown women
up into that cave,

14:37.918 --> 14:41.626
<i>it strikes me so much more
as being a two-man job.</i>

14:44.250 --> 14:47.709
<i>If you go back and look
at all the newspaper articles,</i>

14:47.792 --> 14:49.250
<i>you see
the complete focus being,</i>

14:49.334 --> 14:51.083
<i>this is a crime
committed by two people</i>

14:51.167 --> 14:53.959
<i>because of the hairs.</i>

14:54.042 --> 14:57.250
<i>There was all kinds
of hair evidence
collected at the scene,</i>

14:57.334 --> 15:01.584
and there was
no hair evidence introduced
against Chester at trial.

15:01.667 --> 15:06.167
<i>There were 18 hairs
found in Ms. Oetting's hand,</i>

15:06.250 --> 15:10.250
<i>and there were seven hairs
found on Ms. Murphy's glove.</i>

15:10.334 --> 15:14.667
<i>It clearly looks like the hairs
of the attackers,</i>

15:14.751 --> 15:18.375
<i>and there's
this 1960 lab report that says</i>

15:18.459 --> 15:21.125
<i>it's not Chester's hair
on the glove.</i>

15:21.209 --> 15:24.334
That to me, for sure, would've
been reasonable doubt

15:24.417 --> 15:25.584
back in the day,

15:25.667 --> 15:28.834
<i>and it wasn't even
